<dl id="n50089b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n50" href="#n50089b">N50 (VI.B.37)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n50all.htm#n50089b"> 89(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> lovver chimney <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n50089b"><li>FW 327.32 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/lexma.htm#n50089b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/l39ma.htm#n50089b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n50089b">MS BL 47479-68v</ms> </li><li>JJA 54:132 <a name="mad2" href="../../ff/fdra/mda.htm#mad2">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ma/mad2.htm#n50089b">Draft: II.3&sect;1.2</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The <mark>chimney, lovver</mark>, stands in the room; which name may perhaps be connected with the Scandinavian lyre (Icelandic, lj&oacute;ri); viz., the smoke-hole in the roof or thatch (thack), out of which in olden times, before houses had regular chimneys and &ldquo;<i>lofts</i>&rdquo; (<i>Dan</i>., Loft; <i>Eng</i>., roof, an upper room), the smoke (reek or reik, <i>Dan</i>., <font color="green">[82]</font> R&ouml;g) left the dark (mirk or <i>murk</i>, <i>Dan</i>., m&ouml;rk) room. <small> J.J.A. Worsaae, <a name="JJAW2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JJAW2"><cite title="source">An Account of the Danes and Norwegians in England, Scotland and Ireland</cite></a> (1852) 81f</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
